The stability of the ODE solver¶

In 03-shortest-curves.ipynb, we found the shortest curve on a synthetic generator by using scipy's solve_bvp. There, using the fun_jac parameter did not make a difference - the solver converged both times to equal solutions. In 04-shortest-curves-vae.ipynb, we tried out the ODE solver on a generator from a trained VAE on synthetic data, where it also converged and found the shortest curve.

In this small notebook, we reload the trained VAE from 04-shortest-curves-vae.ipynb and demonstrate that the fun_jac parameter is crucial for convergence, even for a simple generator surface. If it is not used, the solver does not converge. This is unfortunate, since it might transfer to high-dimensional generators as well. However, using the fun_jac parameter involves computing third-order derivatives of the generator's output, which is computationally expensive, especially for high-dimensional outputs.

Reload the model¶

from 04-shortest-curves-vae.ipynb. We need use double floating point precision. As we have seen in 03-shortest-curves-float32.ipynb, single floating point precision can break the convergence of the solver.

Find the shortest curve with fun_jac¶

This yields exactly the same result as in 04-shortest-curves-vae.ipynb: the solver converges quickly to the shortest curve.

Conclustion¶

The fun_jac parameter is computationally expensive, but probably essential to finding a geodesic. Also, it is worth noting, that in 03-shortest-curves-float32.ipynb, we saw that not using fun_jac still works if we use double floating point precision. Here, double or single floating point precision does not make a difference. It converges with fun_jac and does not converge without fun_jac, regardless of whether we use float32 or float64.
